# Burp Suite Logs Guide

# Overview

Burp Suite logs are used to monitor, capture, analyze, 
and record HTTP/HTTPS requests and responses between a client and a web server during web application security testing. 
Logs help penetration testers identify vulnerabilities, track attack attempts, and analyze application behavior.

# Types of Burp Suite Logs

1.Proxy HTTP History

The HTTP History log records all requests and responses passing through Burp Proxy.

# Purpose

* Monitor website traffic
* Analyze parameters and headers
* Identify vulnerabilities
* Track user actions

# Information Included

* Host and IP address
* Request method (GET, POST)
* Status codes
* Content type
* Request/response length
* Cookies and headers

2.Target Site Map Logs
The Site Map stores discovered pages, directories, APIs, and application content.

# Purpose

* Map application structure
* Identify hidden endpoints
* Analyze attack surface

# Information Included

* URLs and directories
* Parameters
* Scripts and APIs
* Application files

3.Scanner Logs

Scanner logs record automated vulnerability scanning activities.

# Purpose

* Detect security vulnerabilities
* Generate issue reports
* Track scan progress

# Common Findings

* SQL Injection
* Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)
* CSRF vulnerabilities
* Security misconfigurations


4.Repeater Logs

Repeater logs store manually modified and repeated HTTP requests.

# Purpose

* Test payloads manually
* Modify requests and parameters
* Validate vulnerabilities

# Activities

* Parameter manipulation
* Authentication testing
* Input validation testing

5. Intruder Attack Logs
Intruder logs record automated attack attempts using payloads.

#Purpose

* Brute-force testing
* Fuzzing
* Parameter testing
* Enumeration attacks

#Information Included

* Payload positions
* Request count
* Response length
* Status codes

6. Sequencer Logs
Sequencer logs analyze randomness and predictability of tokens.

#Purpose

* Test session token security
* Analyze entropy levels
* Detect weak session management


7. Collaborator Logs

Collaborator logs record external interactions triggered during testing.

#Purpose

* Detect SSRF vulnerabilities
* Identify Blind XSS
* Monitor DNS/HTTP interactions

# Important Log Components

| Component    | Description                   |
| ------------ | ----------------------------- |
| Request      | Client request sent to server |
| Response     | Server reply to client        |
| Headers      | Metadata information          |
| Parameters   | User input values             |
| Cookies      | Session management data       |
| Status Codes | HTTP response codes           |
| Payloads     | Attack data used in testing   |


# Common HTTP Status Codes in Logs

| Code    | Meaning               |
| ------- | --------------------- |
| 200     | Successful request    |
| 301/302 | Redirection           |
| 403     | Forbidden access      |
| 404     | Page not found        |
| 500     | Internal server error |


# Importance of Burp Suite Logs

* Helps identify vulnerabilities
* Tracks attack behavior
* Assists in debugging web applications
* Provides evidence during penetration testing
* Improves web application security analysis

# Conclusion
Burp Suite logs are essential for monitoring, analyzing, and documenting web application testing activities.
Proper understanding of logs helps penetration testers efficiently identify security weaknesses and improve application security.

